wledge, and the concomitant politicization of previously taken-for-granted science-policy interfaces, Neves contends that institutions like botanic gardens have discursively deployed postnormal science and posthuman precepts to justify their growing involvement with biodiversity conservation governance within the Anthropocene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBotanical gardens. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aStoett, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTemby, Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438474571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438474571/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles